    <meta name="maintainer" content="amrita.sakthivel@suse.com" its:translate="no"/>
    </info>
  <para>
To understand &selnx; rules , you must have a grasp on &selnx; contexts and how they determine interactions.
&selnx; rules provide a granular level of control , enabling system administrators to implement strong security policies.
  </para>
  <para>&selnx; generally follow this format:</para>
  <screen>allow source target:class permissions;</screen>
  <itemizedlist>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        allow: The <literal>allow</literal> rule defines which operations such as read,write and execute between a source
        and target  are permitted.
              </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para>
       source: The &selnx; context of the process (subject).
      </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para>
       target:The &selnx; context of the resource (object).
      </para>
    </listitem>
        <listitem>
      <para>
        class: The type of object e.g. file,process,socket etc.
      </para>
    </listitem>
     <listitem>
      <para>
        permissions: The allowed actions such as read, write and execute.
        </para>
    </listitem>
  </itemizedlist>
  <para>An example of a &selnx; rule:</para>
  <screen>allow user_t bin_t:file {read execute gettattr}; </screen>
  <para>
  The rule example states that <literal>user_t</literal> is allowed to access objects of the class <literal>file</literal>
  with the context type <literal>bin_t</literal> using permissions <literal>read</literal>, <literal>execute</literal> and <literal>getattr</literal>.
  </para>
</topic>
